Task 1: Understanding Network Interface Management
Subtask 1.1: Using ifconfig Command
The ifconfig command is a traditional tool for configuring and displaying network interface information.

Step 1: Open your terminal and check all network interfaces

ifconfig
Step 2: Display only active interfaces

ifconfig -a
Step 3: Check a specific interface (usually eth0 or enp0s3)

ifconfig eth0
If eth0 doesn't exist, use:

ip link show
Then use the interface name shown (e.g., enp0s3, ens33).

Step 4: Display interface statistics

ifconfig eth0 | grep -E "(RX|TX)"
Subtask 1.2: Using the Modern ip Command
The ip command is the modern replacement for ifconfig and provides more functionality.

Step 1: Display all network interfaces

ip link show
Step 2: Show IP addresses assigned to interfaces

ip addr show
Step 3: Display routing table

ip route show
Step 4: Show detailed interface information

ip -s link show
Step 5: Display only IPv4 addresses

ip -4 addr show
Subtask 1.3: Comparing ifconfig and ip Commands
Create a comparison script to see the differences:

nano network_comparison.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Network Interface Comparison ==="
echo
echo "--- Using ifconfig ---"
ifconfig | head -10
echo
echo "--- Using ip addr ---"
ip addr show | head -10
echo
echo "--- Routing Information ---"
echo "ifconfig route (use route command):"
route -n | head -5
echo
echo "ip route:"
ip route show
Make it executable and run:

chmod +x network_comparison.sh
./network_comparison.sh
Task 2: Network Connection Analysis
Subtask 2.1: Using netstat Command
The netstat command displays network connections, routing tables, and interface statistics.

Step 1: Display all active connections

netstat -a
Step 2: Show only listening ports

netstat -l
Step 3: Display TCP connections with process information

netstat -tlnp
Step 4: Show UDP connections

netstat -ulnp
Step 5: Display routing table using netstat

netstat -rn
Subtask 2.2: Using the Modern ss Command
The ss command is the modern replacement for netstat with better performance.

Step 1: Display all socket connections

ss -a
Step 2: Show listening sockets

ss -l
Step 3: Display TCP sockets with process information

ss -tlnp
Step 4: Show UDP sockets

ss -ulnp
Step 5: Display socket statistics

ss -s
Subtask 2.3: Creating a Network Monitoring Script
Create a comprehensive network monitoring script:

nano network_monitor.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Network Monitoring Report ==="
echo "Generated on: $(date)"
echo

echo "--- Active Network Interfaces ---"
ip link show | grep -E "^[0-9]+:" | awk '{print $2}' | sed 's/://'
echo

echo "--- IP Address Configuration ---"
ip addr show | grep -E "inet " | awk '{print $2, $NF}'
echo

echo "--- Listening Services ---"
echo "TCP Services:"
ss -tlnp | grep LISTEN | head -5
echo
echo "UDP Services:"
ss -ulnp | head -5
echo

echo "--- Network Statistics ---"
ss -s
echo

echo "--- Routing Table ---"
ip route show
Make it executable and run:

chmod +x network_monitor.sh
./network_monitor.sh
Task 3: Network Interface Configuration
Subtask 3.1: Viewing Current Configuration
Step 1: Check current network configuration

ip addr show
Step 2: View current routing configuration

ip route show
Step 3: Check DNS configuration

cat /etc/resolv.conf
Subtask 3.2: Temporary Interface Configuration
Note: These changes are temporary and will be lost after reboot.

Step 1: Add a secondary IP address to an interface (replace eth0 with your interface name)

sudo ip addr add 192.168.100.10/24 dev eth0
Step 2: Verify the new IP address

ip addr show eth0
Step 3: Remove the secondary IP address

sudo ip addr del 192.168.100.10/24 dev eth0
Step 4: Verify removal

ip addr show eth0
Subtask 3.3: Interface State Management
Step 1: Check interface state

ip link show eth0
Step 2: Bring interface down (be careful with this on remote systems)

sudo ip link set eth0 down
Step 3: Bring interface back up

sudo ip link set eth0 up
Step 4: Verify interface state

ip link show eth0
Task 4: Network Connectivity Testing
Subtask 4.1: Using ping Command
Step 1: Test connectivity to localhost

ping -c 4 127.0.0.1
Step 2: Test connectivity to your default gateway

ping -c 4 $(ip route show default | awk '{print $3}')
Step 3: Test connectivity to a public DNS server

ping -c 4 8.8.8.8
Step 4: Test connectivity with hostname resolution

ping -c 4 google.com
Step 5: Continuous ping with timestamp

ping -D google.com
Press Ctrl+C to stop after a few seconds.

Subtask 4.2: Using traceroute Command
Step 1: Install traceroute if not available

sudo apt update && sudo apt install traceroute -y
Or on Red Hat-based systems:

sudo yum install traceroute -y
Step 2: Trace route to a public server

traceroute google.com
Step 3: Trace route with IP addresses only

traceroute -n google.com
Step 4: Trace route to your default gateway

traceroute $(ip route show default | awk '{print $3}')
Subtask 4.3: Creating a Connectivity Test Script
Create a comprehensive connectivity testing script:

nano connectivity_test.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Network Connectivity Test ==="
echo "Test started at: $(date)"
echo

# Test localhost
echo "--- Testing Localhost ---"
if ping -c 2 127.0.0.1 > /dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "✓ Localhost connectivity: OK"
else
    echo "✗ Localhost connectivity: FAILED"
fi

# Test default gateway
GATEWAY=$(ip route show default | awk '{print $3}')
if [ ! -z "$GATEWAY" ]; then
    echo "--- Testing Default Gateway ($GATEWAY) ---"
    if ping -c 2 $GATEWAY > /dev/null 2>&1; then
        echo "✓ Gateway connectivity: OK"
    else
        echo "✗ Gateway connectivity: FAILED"
    fi
else
    echo "✗ No default gateway found"
fi

# Test DNS
echo "--- Testing DNS Resolution ---"
if ping -c 2 google.com > /dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "✓ DNS resolution: OK"
else
    echo "✗ DNS resolution: FAILED"
fi

# Test external connectivity
echo "--- Testing External Connectivity ---"
if ping -c 2 8.8.8.8 > /dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "✓ External connectivity: OK"
else
    echo "✗ External connectivity: FAILED"
fi

echo
echo "Test completed at: $(date)"
Make it executable and run:

chmod +x connectivity_test.sh
./connectivity_test.sh
Task 5: Advanced Network Analysis
Subtask 5.1: Port Scanning and Service Detection
Step 1: Check what services are listening on your system

ss -tlnp | grep LISTEN
Step 2: Check for specific ports

ss -tlnp | grep :22    # SSH
ss -tlnp | grep :80    # HTTP
ss -tlnp | grep :443   # HTTPS
Step 3: Use netcat to test port connectivity

# Install netcat if needed
sudo apt install netcat -y

# Test if a port is open (example: SSH on localhost)
nc -zv localhost 22
Subtask 5.2: Network Interface Statistics
Step 1: Monitor network interface statistics

watch -n 2 'cat /proc/net/dev'
Press Ctrl+C to stop after observing for a few seconds.

Step 2: Display detailed interface statistics

ip -s link show
Step 3: Monitor real-time network activity

# Install iftop if available
sudo apt install iftop -y 2>/dev/null || echo "iftop not available, using alternative"

# Alternative: use ss to monitor connections
watch -n 2 'ss -tuln | head -10'
Subtask 5.3: Creating a Network Diagnostic Script
Create a comprehensive diagnostic script:

nano network_diagnostic.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Complete Network Diagnostic Report ==="
echo "Generated: $(date)"
echo "Hostname: $(hostname)"
echo "User: $(whoami)"
echo

echo "--- System Network Configuration ---"
echo "Kernel version: $(uname -r)"
echo "Network interfaces:"
ip link show | grep -E "^[0-9]+:" | awk '{print "  " $2}' | sed 's/://'
echo

echo "--- IP Configuration ---"
ip addr show | grep -E "inet " | while read line; do
    echo "  $line"
done
echo

echo "--- Routing Information ---"
echo "Default gateway: $(ip route show default | awk '{print $3}')"
echo "Routing table:"
ip route show | while read line; do
    echo "  $line"
done
echo

echo "--- DNS Configuration ---"
echo "DNS servers:"
grep nameserver /etc/resolv.conf | while read line; do
    echo "  $line"
done
echo

echo "--- Active Connections ---"
echo "Listening TCP ports:"
ss -tlnp | grep LISTEN | head -5 | while read line; do
    echo "  $line"
done
echo

echo "--- Connectivity Tests ---"
echo -n "Localhost: "
ping -c 1 127.0.0.1 > /dev/null 2>&1 && echo "OK" || echo "FAILED"

GATEWAY=$(ip route show default | awk '{print $3}')
if [ ! -z "$GATEWAY" ]; then
    echo -n "Gateway ($GATEWAY): "
    ping -c 1 $GATEWAY > /dev/null 2>&1 && echo "OK" || echo "FAILED"
fi

echo -n "External (8.8.8.8): "
ping -c 1 8.8.8.8 > /dev/null 2>&1 && echo "OK" || echo "FAILED"

echo -n "DNS Resolution: "
ping -c 1 google.com > /dev/null 2>&1 && echo "OK" || echo "FAILED"

echo
echo "=== Diagnostic Complete ==="
Make it executable and run:

chmod +x network_diagnostic.sh
./network_diagnostic.sh
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Command Not Found
If you encounter "command not found" errors:

# For ifconfig
sudo apt install net-tools -y

# For traceroute
sudo apt install traceroute -y

# For netcat
sudo apt install netcat -y
Issue 2: Permission Denied
If you get permission errors when modifying network settings:

# Always use sudo for network configuration changes
sudo ip addr add 192.168.1.100/24 dev eth0
Issue 3: Interface Names
Different systems use different interface naming conventions:

# Check your actual interface names
ip link show
Common names include: eth0, enp0s3, ens33, wlan0

Key Concepts Summary
ifconfig: Traditional tool for network interface configuration
ip: Modern, more powerful replacement for ifconfig
netstat: Traditional tool for displaying network connections
ss: Modern, faster replacement for netstat
ping: Tests basic connectivity using ICMP packets
traceroute: Shows the path packets take to reach a destination
